-- 
Taiwan Stocks: Catcher, Coretronic, HTC, Realtek, Siliconware

-- B y   W e i y i   L i m
-- 
2011-07-19T06:05:40Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-19/catcher-china-steel-formosa-plastics-taiwan-stocks-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in Taiwan trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of 1:30 p.m. close in Taipei.  The Taiex Index fell 14 points, or 0.2 percent, to
8,524.57.  Catcher Technology Co. (2474 TT) surged by the 6.9 percent
daily limit to NT$224.50, the highest close since Jan. 25, 2007.
The casing maker had its share-price estimate raised 22 percent
to NT$304 at Citigroup Inc., which said the company is “ahead
of the competition” by 12 months to 16 months. The brokerage
kept its “buy” rating on the stock. The company also had its
price estimate increased to NT$300 from NT$246 at Macquarie
Group Ltd. Bank of America-Merrill Lynch raised the price
estimate to NT$270 from NT$221 in a report today.  Coretronic Corp. (5371)  (5371 TT) dropped 3.3 percent to NT$31.90,
the lowest close since June 24, 2009, after its stock rating was
cut to “underperform” from “outperform” at Macquarie Group
Ltd. The brokerage cited the potential for a “big earnings
miss” and “overall poor execution” for the downgrade.  Formosa Plastics Corp. (1301)  (1301 TT) dropped 0.9 percent to
NT$109.  Formosa Chemicals & Fibre Corp. (1326)  (1326 TT) retreated 1.5
percent to NT$102.  China  rejected Formosa Plastics Group’s plan
to build chemical plants in China’s Ningbo city, the Economic
Daily News reported today, citing statements from the Zhejiang
government. The Taiwanese company had planned to invest $4.5
billion in Ningbo, according to the report. Chueh Ching-hsien, a
public relations officer at the group, denied the report when
called today.  HTC Corp. (2498)  (2498 TT) gained 2.5 percent to NT$893, snapping
two days of losses, before the stock goes ex-dividend tomorrow.
The smartphone maker plans to pay a 2010 cash dividend of NT$37
a share and 50 shares for each 1,000 currently held, the
Taoyuan, Taiwan-based company said in an exchange filing on
April 30.  MediaTek Inc. (2454)  (2454 TT) rallied 3.4 percent to NT$259.50.
The chip designer will cooperate with the Wideband Code Division
Multiple Access industry, a technology supported by Apple Inc.’s
iPhone, on development and marketing, the company said in a
statement on its website yesterday. The stock lost 4.6 percent
to NT$251 yesterday.  Realtek Semiconductor Corp. (2379)  (2379 TT), a chip designer,
climbed 6.9 percent to NT$51.30, the biggest advance since Sept.
3, after the company was raised to “equal-weight” from
“underweight” at Morgan Stanley. The brokerage recommends
long-term investors “buy on weakness.”  Siliconware Precision Industry Co. (2325 TT), the chip-
packaging and testing company, slid 5 percent to NT$28.40, the
lowest close since Feb. 20, 2009, after it was cut to
“neutral” from “overweight” at JPMorgan Chase & Co in a
report dated yesterday.  To contact the reporter on this story:
